  "signature": "ed25519:b7d3e1f9a2c4b6d8e0f2a4c6d8e0f2a4c6d8e0f2a4c6d8e0f2a4c6d8e0f2a4c6",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software used in the ensemble (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1) must be under documented version control with regression testing records available.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1 is a commercially validated solver with documented QA procedures, ISO 9001 certification, and internal regression test suites. DePuy Synthes and FDA both operate under 21 CFR Part 820 quality systems. Version control logs and release notes are on file. Achieved level 3 (formal QA system with documented testing)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems representative of beam bending and contact mechanics must be solved with known analytical solutions; error < 1%.",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble was verified against NAFEMS benchmark LE1 (plane stress) and a cantilever beam bending case with Hertzian contact. Errors in all benchmark QoIs were below 0.5%. Code verification is documented in the modeling report appendix. Required and achieved level 2 (standard benchmarks with documented results)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change < 2% between the penultimate and final mesh refinement levels.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. Construct stiffness changed by 1.1% and yield force by 0.8% between the medium and fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation confirmed grid convergence index < 1.5%. Discretization error is well-controlled at the required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual norms must converge below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance error < 0.1%.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear load steps converged with force residuals below 1e-7 and displacement residuals below 1e-8. Energy balance was checked at each increment; maximum error was 0.04%. Solver log files are archived. Achieved level 2 (documented convergence monitoring)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "An independent analyst must review boundary condition setup, material assignments, and contact definitions prior to submission.",
      "rationale": "An independent FDA biomedical engineer reviewed the model setup, boundary conditions (fixed inferior block, axial-offset load per ASTM F1717), material assignments (Ti-6Al-4V, UHMWPE block), and contact definitions (frictional, mu=0.2 at screw-rod interface). No use errors were identified. Peer review checklist is on file."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model must capture elasto-plastic behavior of Ti-6Al-4V with isotropic hardening; contact must be modeled with friction.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity (E=114 GPa, sigma_y=880 MPa, E_t=1.14 GPa) was applied to all titanium components based on published material data and coupon testing. Frictional contact (Coulomb, mu=0.2) was applied at all metal-metal interfaces. The model form is consistent with the physics of the compression-bending test and has been used in prior published FDA studies. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions must be traceable to measured values from the specific device lot used in bench testing; uncertainty bounds must be documented.",
      "rationale": "Geometric dimensions were obtained from CMM measurements of the actual test articles (7.5 mm screw, 5.5 mm rod, 100 mm construct). Material properties were sourced from mill certificates for the specific titanium alloy lot. Dimensional uncertainty (±0.01 mm) and material property uncertainty (±2%) were propagated through a sensitivity analysis. Achieved level 3 (measured inputs with documented uncertainty)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 6 test specimens from production lot; specimen dimensions verified by CMM prior to testing.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs were assembled from production-representative components. All specimens were dimensionally verified by CMM; mean screw diameter 7.49 mm (SD 0.005 mm). Specimens were distributed across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes) to assess inter-laboratory variability. Sample size exceeds the minimum requirement. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two offset distances per ASTM F1717.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single ASTM F1717 offset distance (44 mm). While this is the standard offset, the clinical loading environment may include varying offset distances corresponding to different patient anatomies. Only one test condition was evaluated, limiting the ability to assess model performance across the full COU envelope. Achieved level 2 (single condition tested); required level 3 (multiple conditions needed for this risk level). This is a documented gap acknowledged in the V&V plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters must be matched to experimental conditions within documented tolerances; any discrepancies must be justified.",
      "rationale": "All FEA boundary conditions were set to match the experimental setup: 44 mm offset, displacement-controlled loading at 5 mm/min (quasi-static), fixed inferior block. Material properties were matched to mill certificates. The UHMWPE block stiffness was calibrated from a separate characterization test. No unresolved parameter discrepancies were identified. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% for all primary QoIs; comparison must account for experimental variability.",
      "rationale": "All three primary QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) met both acceptance criteria. E/uval values were 0.87, 1.34, and 1.12 respectively. Percent differences were 4.2%, 6.1%, and 5.7%. Experimental uncertainty was estimated from inter-laboratory and inter-specimen variability. Achieved level 3 (rigorous quantitative comparison with uncertainty)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation must be the same as or directly transformable to QoIs used in the COU decision.",
      "rationale": "The three validation QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are identical to the QoIs used in the regulatory submission decision. No transformation or surrogate QoIs are required. The QoIs are directly clinically interpretable as indicators of construct mechanical integrity. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be evaluated for their relevance to the specific clinical context of use, including patient population, implant configuration, and loading environment.",
      "rationale": "The assessment team determined that this factor does not meaningfully apply to the present COU because the validation is a direct bench-to-model comparison under ASTM F1717 conditions, which are themselves a regulatory standard for this device class. The team reasoned that relevance of the validation activities is implicitly established by regulatory precedent for ASTM F1717 as the accepted surrogate for in vivo pedicle screw loading, and therefore no formal relevance assessment was conducted. The factor was not scored and no requiredLevel or achievedLevel was assigned. This reasoning conflates regulatory acceptability of the test standard with a formal V&V 40 relevance evaluation and does not constitute a proper assessment of whether the bench conditions adequately represent the clinical loading spectrum for this specific patient population and implant configuration."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA ensemble meets all pre-established acceptance criteria for the three primary QoIs under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors were formally assessed; eleven achieved their required level. The Test conditions factor achieved level 2 against a required level 3, representing a documented gap that is mitigated by the direct regulatory applicability of the ASTM F1717 standard and the inter-laboratory validation design. The Relevance of the validation activities factor was not formally assessed on the basis that ASTM F1717 is an established regulatory standard for this device class; the team concluded the factor does not require additional evaluation in this context. Overall credibility is judged sufficient to support a Medium assurance level decision for a Class II device at modelRiskLevel 3.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
